##Type of Network Models
There are two main network models which are classified as De-facto and De jure. The TCP/IP model is known as the De-facto model and the OSI reference model is
known as De jure. Initially, the TCP/IP model was created and implemented with its 4 layers. Afterwards, OSI model was proposed which added 3 extra layers alongside
the layers of TCP/IP. But at implementation, it was not found to be efficient enough hence OSI model is mainly studied theoretically and is a reference model for 
learning and TCP/IP is widely used everywhere.

##OSI model layers:
7. Application layer: email, web browsers
6. Presentation layer: Data translation, encryption, compression
5. Session layer: Dialog control, synchronization. Starts/stops conversation between apps.
4. Transport layer: Breaks data into chunks, checks for errors.
3. Network layer: Finds route(addressing)
2. Data Link layer: Moves data within same local network(MAC addr.)
1. Physical layer: Cables, radio signals, electric pulses.

##TCP/IP model layers:
4. Application layer: OSI model 7,6,5
3. Transport layer: OSI model 4
2. Internet/Network layer: OSI model 3
1. Network access layer: OSI model 1,2




